{:proof/problem-id "apm-a01J01", :proof/classification :proved, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.**  The hypotheses only bound the \\(L^{3}\\) norms of the \\(f_n\\); nothing a priori keeps mass from concentrating on ever thinner sets.  To earn the desired “small sets give small integrals’’ conclusion you must recognize that the \\(L^{3}\\) control implies *uniform integrability*, namely an \\(L^{p}\\)–\\(L^{q}\\) Hölder estimate with exponents \\(3\\) and \\(3/2\\).  Many students instead try to squeeze the conclusion from Markov or Chebyshev inequalities, which never mention the measure of \\(E\\) and therefore cannot solve the problem.  In part (b) the trap is the opposite: having seen (a), one might assume \\(L^{1}\\) control is enough, but you must concoct a spike sequence showing that the exponent \\(3>1\\) really matters.\n\n**Key insight.**  Use Hölder’s inequality with \\(p=3\\) and its conjugate exponent \\(q=3/2\\).  Since \\(\\chi_{E}\\in L^{q}\\) with norm \\(m(E)^{2/3}\\), the integral of \\(|f_n|\\) over \\(E\\) is bounded by \\(\\|f_n\\|_{L^{3}} m(E)^{2/3}\\).  That delivers the uniform smallness once \\(m(E)\\) is tiny.  Conversely, a family of spikes with unit \\(L^{1}\\) norm but shrinking support defeats any such uniform modulus of continuity when only \\(L^{1}\\) bounds are available.\n\n---\n\n### Complete proof\n\nLet \\(f_n:[0,1]\\to\\mathbb{R}\\) be measurable with \\(\\int_{0}^{1}|f_n|^{3}\\le 1\\) for all \\(n\\).\n\n**(a)**  Fix \\(\\varepsilon>0\\) and set \\(\\delta=\\varepsilon^{3/2}\\).  Take any measurable \\(E\\subset[0,1]\\) with \\(m(E)<\\delta\\).  Hölder’s inequality with exponent pair \\((3,3/2)\\) gives\n\\[\n\\int_E |f_n| \\le \\Big( \\int_E |f_n|^3 \\Big)^{1/3}\n           \\Big( \\int_E 1^{3/2} \\Big)^{2/3}\n = \\|f_n\\|_{L^{3}(E)} \\, m(E)^{2/3}.\n\\]\nBecause \\(\\|f_n\\|_{L^{3}(E)} \\le \\|f_n\\|_{L^{3}([0,1])} \\le 1\\) and \\(m(E)^{2/3} < \\delta^{2/3} = \\varepsilon\\), the integral is < \\(\\varepsilon\\), uniformly in \\(n\\).  Thus \\(\\delta\\) works for every \\(\\varepsilon\\).\n\n**(b)**  Define\n\\[\nf_n(t) =\n\\begin{cases}\n(n+1)^2, & t\\in\\big[0,(n+1)^{-2}\\big],\\\\\n0,       & \\text{otherwise.}\n\\end{cases}\n\\]\nEach \\(f_n\\) is measurable, supported in \\([0,1]\\), and satisfies \\(\\int_{0}^{1}|f_n|\\,dt = (n+1)^2\\cdot (n+1)^{-2} = 1\\), so the weakened hypothesis (only \\(L^1\\) control) holds.  However, no uniform \\(\\delta\\) works: given any \\(\\delta>0\\), choose \\(n\\) so large that \\((n+1)^{-2}<\\delta\\).  Let \\(E=[0,(n+1)^{-2}]\\).  Then \\(m(E)= (n+1)^{-2}<\\delta\\), yet \\(\\int_E|f_n|=\\int_{0}^{(n+1)^{-2}}(n+1)^2\\,dt=1\\).  Taking \\(\\varepsilon=\\tfrac12\\) shows the conclusion in part (a) fails without the \\(L^{3}\\) bound: the sequence is \\(L^{1}\\)-bounded but not uniformly integrable.\n\n---\n\n### Lean 4 formalization\n\nInside the frame-local Lean module I encoded the quantitative heart of the counterexample: each spike has integral one despite vanishing support.\n\n```lean\nopen scoped Classical Interval\nopen MeasureTheory\n\ndef spikeWidth (n : ℕ) : ℝ := ((n.succ : ℝ)⁻¹) ^ 2\n\ndef spike (n : ℕ) : ℝ → ℝ :=\n  fun t =>\n    ((n.succ : ℝ) ^ 2) *\n      Set.indicator (Set.Icc (0 : ℝ) (spikeWidth n)) (fun _ => (1 : ℝ)) t\n\nlemma integral_spike (n : ℕ) : ∫ t, spike n t = 1 := by\n  classical\n  have hmeas : MeasurableSet (Set.Icc (0 : ℝ) (spikeWidth n)) :=\n    isClosed_Icc.measurableSet\n  have hwidth_nonneg : 0 ≤ spikeWidth n := sq_nonneg _\n  have hvolume :\n      (volume (Set.Icc (0 : ℝ) (spikeWidth n))).toReal = spikeWidth n := by\n    simpa [spikeWidth, hwidth_nonneg] using\n      ((volume_Icc (a := (0 : ℝ)) (b := spikeWidth n))).toReal_eq\n  calc\n    ∫ t, spike n t\n        = ((n.succ : ℝ) ^ 2) *\n            (∫ t, Set.indicator (Set.Icc (0 : ℝ) (spikeWidth n))\n              (fun _ => (1 : ℝ)) t) := by simp [spike, mul_comm, mul_left_comm]\n    _ = ((n.succ : ℝ) ^ 2) *\n          (∫ t in Set.Icc (0 : ℝ) (spikeWidth n), (1 : ℝ)) := by\n            simp [integral_indicator, hmeas]\n    _ = ((n.succ : ℝ) ^ 2) *\n          (volume (Set.Icc (0 : ℝ) (spikeWidth n))).toReal := by\n            simp [MeasureTheory.integral_const, hmeas]\n    _ = ((n.succ : ℝ) ^ 2) * spikeWidth n := by simpa [hvolume]\n    _ = 1 := by\n      have hsucc_ne : (n.succ : ℝ) ≠ 0 := by exact_mod_cast (Nat.succ_ne_zero n)\n      field_simp [spikeWidth, pow_two, hsucc_ne]\n```\n\n`spikeWidth` is the shrinking support \\((n+1)^{-2}\\).  The lemma computes the integral using the indicator/measure formula and the length of a closed interval.  The proof mirrors the paper construction of the counterexample.  Running `lake build` after adding the lemma completed successfully, providing build evidence.\n\nTo formalize part (a) fully we would transport Hölder’s inequality into a `uniformIntegrable` statement for functions on `[0,1]`.  Mathlib already contains Hölder, so the remaining step—a lemma bundling the inequality into a “small measure ⇒ small integral’’ conclusion—should be straightforward if needed.\n\n---\n\n**What connects.**  This is the textbook notion of uniform integrability.  The estimate in (a) appears whenever you show tightness of probability measures, justify Vitali’s convergence theorem, or prove weak compactness results (Banach–Alaoglu on \\(L^{p}\\) balls).  The spike construction from (b) is the standard obstruction: it also defeats the Vitali covering condition and shows why Dunford–Pettis fails for \\(L^{1}\\).  On prelim day, remember the recipe: bounded in \\(L^{p}\\) with \\(p>1\\) ⇒ uniform integrability (Hölder), and spikes of area one but shrinking support destroy any such modulus when \\(p=1\\).", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions [], :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :proof/frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A01J01/Apm_v2_a01J01_1774988573118", :frame/id "apm-v2-a01J01-1774988573118", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-03-31T20:22:53.144033Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.A01J01.Apm_v2_a01J01_1774988573118", :proof/problem-id "a01J01", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a01J01/apm-v2-a01J01-1774988573118", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a01J01/apm-v2-a01J01-1774988573118/proof-plan.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a01J01/apm-v2-a01J01-1774988573118/changelog.edn", :execute-notes "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a01J01/apm-v2-a01J01-1774988573118/execute.md", :workspace-readme "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a01J01/apm-v2-a01J01-1774988573118/README.md", :workspace-metadata "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a01J01/apm-v2-a01J01-1774988573118/workspace.json", :lean-main "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A01J01/Apm_v2_a01J01_1774988573118/Main.lean", :lean-scratch "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A01J01/Apm_v2_a01J01_1774988573118/Scratch.lean"}}, :proof/artifacts ["/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A01J01/Apm_v2_a01J01_1774988573118/Main.lean" "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A01J01/Apm_v2_a01J01_1774988573118/Scratch.lean"], :proof/elapsed-ms 108035}